{{For|the modern historian|A. J. P. Taylor}}
'''Arnold Joseph Taylor''' [[CBE]] (1911–2002) was a distinguished medieval [[historian]] who was an international expert on European [[castle]] building. His work on [[Edward I of England|Edward I]]'s Welsh castles is particularly notable, particularly his identification of the origins of the architect in Savoy (now Switzerland). He was Chief Inspector of Ancient Monuments and Historic Buildings at the [[Ministry of Works (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Works]] (later the Ministry of Public Building and Works and the [[Secretary of State for the Environment|Department of the Environment]]) from 1961 to 1972.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Saunders|first1=Andrew|title=Arnold Joseph Taylor 1911–2002|journal=Proceedings of the British Academy|date=January 2007|issue=138 Biographical Memoirs of Fellows, V|url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.5871/bacad/9780197263938.003.0017|accessdate=8 November 2014|doi=10.5871/bacad/9780197263938.003.0017}}</ref><ref name=Telegraph>{{cite news|title=Arnold Taylor (obituary)|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1414922/Arnold-Taylor.html|accessdate=8 November 2014|work=Daily Telegraph|date=2 December 2002}}</ref>
Arnold Joseph Taylor was born in London on 24 July 1911. He was educated at the [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylors' School]] and at [[St. John's College, Oxford]], where he read history. After obtaining a diploma in education he became a schoolteacher at [[Chard, Somerset|Chard]] School in Somerset.<ref name=Telegraph/>
In 1935 joined the Ministry of Works as Assistant Inspector in the Ancient Monuments office. After [[World War II|wartime]] service in [[RAF Intelligence]] he was appointed Inspector of Ancient Monuments for Wales, with responsibility for the [[Castles in Great Britain and Ireland#Welsh principalities and Edwardian castles|Edwardian castles of North Wales]], on which be became an expert. He was promoted to Assistant Chief Inspector in 1954 and to Chief Inspector in 1961, which he remained until retirement in 1972.<ref name=Telegraph/>
In 1940 Taylor married Patricia Guilbride; they had one son and one daughter. He died in Compton, Surrey on 24 October 2002, aged 91.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saunders |first1=Andrew |title=Arnold Taylor, Inspector of ancient monuments |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/arnold-taylor-603616.html |accessdate=8 November 2014 |work=The Independent |date=8 November 2002 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100429171512/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/arnold-taylor-603616.html |archivedate=April 29, 2010 }}</ref>
==Awards and public appointments== *[[Freeman of the City of London]] (1959) *[[CBE]] (1971) *[[Fellow of the British Academy]] (1972) *[[Society of Antiquaries of London|Society of Antiquaries]]; president 1975–78 *[[London and Middlesex Archaeological Society]], president 1971–73
